<subSubSection lastPageId="1" lastPageNumber="42" pageId="0" pageNumber="41" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="0.[151,1436,1970,2030]" lastBlockId="1.[151,1436,151,247]" lastPageId="1" lastPageNumber="42" pageId="0" pageNumber="41">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,273,1970,1995]" pageId="0" pageNumber="41">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Body slender, flat, depressed, always covered with delicate fine scales; head short, the clypeus extending onto the dorsum of the head; the entire rostrum composed of the clypeus; pronotum longer than wide, especially elongate in males compared to females; male micropterous, but female always apterous; fore tibia with only inner tympanum; hind tibia with dorsal spinules, but without movable large spines; middle tarsomeres with developed pulvillus; male phallic complex mostly membranous; ovipositor needle-shaped.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
